An iterator itself cannot be compared. You must _iterate_ over it to get the values of the underlying collection (that&#39;s where the name comes from).

```
final Iterator&lt;Character&gt; asc = L.iterator();
final Iterator&lt;Character&gt; desc = L.descendingIterator();

// both iterators have the same underlying collection, so `hasNext` _must_ return the same value for both
while(asc.hasNext() &amp;&amp; desc.hasNext()) {
  if (!Objects.equals(asc.next(), desc.next()) {
    // characters are different, definitely not a palindrome
    return false;
  }
}

// both iterators fully consumed without finding an offending character =&gt; a palindrome was found
return true;
```

`Iterator#hasNext` checks if there are more elements that have not yet been visited. `Iterator#next` moves the iterator forward by one, i.e. it consumes the element, and returns it.

A few more observations about your code:

* `==` compares memory addresses, not the values of objects
* `Iterator` instances do not implement `equals`, as such they cannot be compared
* No need to create a new `LinkedListDeque` since `LinkedList` already implements `Deque`
* `ArrayDeque` is another Deque type that does not suffer from the same memory overhead as `LinkedList`
* This algorithm fully iterates over the deque twice, forward and backward; which is inefficient (double the amount of work). It would suffice to stop when both iterators meet in the middle (but the iterator interface does not provide such functionality. Perhaps using a `ListIterator` could help avoid this). For simple and short inputs this won&#39;t be a problem though.

